	\text{(transpose m)} 		& \text{returns the matrix}\;{\bf n}, \cr
		& \text{where}\; n_{ij} = m_{ji}. \cr
}  \]
@end tex
We can define the dot product as@footnote{This definition uses the extended
version of @code{map} described in @ref{Footnote 78}.}

@lisp
(define (dot-product v w)
  (accumulate + 0 (map * v w)))
@end lisp

